No, you do not have to manually rethrow exceptions at each level unless you need to perform specific cleanup or logging at each level of the call stack.

In C++, when an exception is thrown, the runtime will automatically "unwind" the stack, meaning it will exit out of each function that was called until it finds a try-catch block that can handle the exception. If there is no such block found, the program will terminate and typically an error message will be output.

So, you only need to catch and potentially rethrow an exception at a certain level if you have a specific reason for doing so, such as:

- Logging the exception
- Modifying the exception or wrapping it in another exception
- Performing cleanup that is specific to the current scope (e.g., releasing resources)

If you just want to observe or handle the exception at the top level (`MethodA` in your example), you can allow the exception to propagate up naturally by not catching it in `MethodB` or `MethodC`.

Here is a simple example to illustrate:

```cpp
void MethodC() {
    // Something went wrong, throw an exception
    throw std::runtime_error("An error occurred in MethodC");
}

void MethodB() {
    // Call MethodC; don't need to catch the exception here unless you need to do some cleanup or logging
    MethodC();
}

void MethodA() {
    try {
        MethodB();
    } catch (const std::runtime_error& e) {
        // Handle exception or log
        std::cerr << "Exception caught in MethodA: " << e.what() << std::endl;
        // Potentially handle the error or rethrow the exception
        throw; // optionally rethrow if you wish to propagate the exception further up the stack
    }
}

int main() {
    try {
        MethodA();
    } catch(const std::exception& e) {
        // If MethodA rethrows, handle it here
        std::cerr << "Exception caught in main: " << e.what() << std::endl;
    }
    return 0;
}
```

In this example, `MethodA` is the only function that has a try-catch block to handle errors from `MethodB` or `MethodC`. You can see that there's no need to handle the exception in `MethodB` unless it has specific cleanup or logging requirements.

If no catch blocks are found that can handle the specific type of exception thrown, the stack will continue unwinding all the way up to `main`, and if `main` doesn't catch it, then the program will terminate with an unhandled exception.

