        catch (...) {
            SetDrawColor(oldColor);
            throw;  // Rethrow the current exception
        }

        SetDrawColor(oldColor);
    }

    // ...
};
```

Then, you can use `WithColor` in your other methods like this:

```cpp
void Renderer::DrawRect(const Rect& rect, const Color& color) {
    WithColor(color, [&]() {
        // Your drawing logic here
        DrawRect(rect);
    });
}

void Renderer::DrawRects(const std::vector<Rect>& rects, const Color& color) {
    WithColor(color, [&]() {
        // Your drawing logic here
        DrawRects(rects);
    });
}
```

In this solution:

1. The `WithColor` method is a template that accepts any callable as its second argument. 
2. You set the new color before executing the drawing code and always restore the old color afterward, even if an exception occurs.
3. When calling `WithColor`, you pass a lambda that contains the appropriate drawing logic. 

This simplifies your code and avoids duplication; the logic for setting and restoring the color is centralized, making it easier to maintain and less error-prone. This pattern is sometimes referred to as "execute around" because it executes arbitrary code "around" a common setup and teardown or a resource management mechanism.

In the line `template <typename DrawFunction>`, `DrawFunction` is the name of the template type parameter. It's a placeholder for any callable type that the user of `WithColor` might pass to the function. This could be a lambda, a functor, or a pointer to a member function, for example.

When defining a template function, you don't define the types that the template can operate on—you instead defer that decision until the function is actually called. At the point of calling the function, the compiler deduces the correct type to substitute for `DrawFunction` based on the argument provided.

Here's a simplified example:

```cpp
template <typename SomeFunction>
void CallFunction(SomeFunction f) {
    f();  // Call the passed-in function
}

int main() {
    CallFunction([]() {
        // This is a lambda function that will be passed to CallFunction
        std::cout << "Hello from lambda!" << std::endl;
    });

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, the type `SomeFunction` is a placeholder for whatever type the lambda expression has. The compiler knows how to deduce that type when you actually make the call to `CallFunction`.

In your case with the `WithColor` function, the type for `DrawFunction` will be deduced similarly when you call `WithColor` and pass a lambda (or any other callable) as the `drawFunc` parameter. This makes the function template highly flexible, as it can operate with any kind of function-like entity.
